Let's break this problem down. We want to find a polynomial with integer coefficients that has the root  $1 - \sqrt[3]{2} + \sqrt[3]{4}$.  

A clever trick is to let $a = 1 - \sqrt[3]{2} + \sqrt[3]{4}$. Now we want to find a polynomial $P(a) = 0$.

Let's cube the expression for $a$:

\begin{align*}
a^3 &= (1 - \sqrt[3]{2} + \sqrt[3]{4})^3 \\
&= 1 - 3\sqrt[3]{2} + 3\sqrt[3]{4} - 2\sqrt[3]{8} + 3\sqrt[3]{2^2 \cdot 4} - 3\sqrt[3]{2 \cdot 4^2} + \sqrt[3]{4^3} \\
&= 1 - 3\sqrt[3]{2} + 3\sqrt[3]{4} - 2 \cdot 2 + 3\sqrt[3]{16} - 3\sqrt[3]{32} + 4 \\
&= 3 - 3\sqrt[3]{2} + 3\sqrt[3]{4} + 3 \cdot 2\sqrt[3]{2} - 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 2\sqrt[3]{2} \\
&= 3 - 3\sqrt[3]{2} + 3\sqrt[3]{4} + 6\sqrt[3]{2} - 12\sqrt[3]{2} \\
&= 3 - 9\sqrt[3]{2} + 3\sqrt[3]{4}
\end{align*}

We can rewrite this in terms of $a$ since we know $a = 1 - \sqrt[3]{2} + \sqrt[3]{4}$:

\begin{align*}
a^3 &= 3 - 9(1 - a + \sqrt[3]{4}) + 3\sqrt[3]{4} \\
&= 3 - 9 + 9a - 9\sqrt[3]{4} + 3\sqrt[3]{4} \\
&= 9a - 6 - 6\sqrt[3]{4}
\end{align*}

Now, let's rearrange and cube both sides to get rid of the cube root:

\begin{align*}
a^3 - 9a + 6 &= -6\sqrt[3]{4} \\
(a^3 - 9a + 6)^3 &= (-6\sqrt[3]{4})^3 \\
a^9 - 27a^7 + 243a^5 - 810a^3 + 1458a + 648 &= 0
\end{align*}

This polynomial,  $P(x) = x^9 - 27x^7 + 243x^5 - 810x^3 + 1458x + 648$, has integer coefficients and $1 - \sqrt[3]{2} + \sqrt[3]{4}$ as a root.

